{"id":"1610.07879","submitter":"Stephan Deschner","authors":"Stephan C. Deschner, Tobias F. Illenseer, Wolfgang J. Duschl","title":"Self-similar solutions to isothermal shock problems","comments":"24 pages, 15 figures","journal-ref":"SIAM J.Appl.Math. 78(1) (2018) 80-103","doi":"10.1137/16M109973X","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn astro-ph.HE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate exact solutions for isothermal shock problems in different\none-dimensional geometries. These solutions are given as analytical expressions\nif possible, or are computed using standard numerical methods for solving\nordinary differential equations. We test the numerical solutions against the\nanalytical expressions to verify the correctness of all numerical algorithms.\nWe use similarity methods to derive a system of ordinary differential equations\n(ODE) yielding exact solutions for power law density distributions as initial\nconditions. Further, the system of ODEs accounts for implosion problems (IP) as\nwell as explosion problems (EP) by changing the initial or boundary conditions,\nrespectively. Taking genuinely isothermal approximations into account leads to\nadditional insights of EPs in contrast to earlier models. We neglect a constant\ninitial energy contribution but introduce a parameter to adjust the initial\nmass distribution of the system. Moreover, we show that due to this parameter a\nconstant initial density is not allowed for isothermal EPs. Reasonable\nrestrictions for this parameter are given. Both, the (genuinely) isothermal\nimplosion as well as the explosion problem are solved for the first time.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 20 Oct 2016 09:14:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 3 Apr 2017 11:38:34 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 26 Jul 2017 10:00:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-02-20"}
